A surreal image of a dog partially obscured by swirling clouds of white and gray smoke, creating an otherworldly and almost spectral atmosphere. The dog’s gaze is fixed forward, solemn and intense, as if caught in a moment of ritual or accident. In the foreground, a large sandwich rests on a weathered wooden surface. The sandwich is overflowing with shredded meat, crisp bacon, and torn lettuce, its contents scattered chaotically across the table. Pieces of meat and debris appear suspended in midair, caught within the smoke, as though the explosion of food has frozen in time. The light is dramatic, slanting in from the left, highlighting the haze and lending the scene a painterly, dreamlike quality. The peeling, distressed wall in the background adds to the sense of decay and tension, transforming an ordinary subject—a dog and a meal—into a haunting tableau that feels part kitchen accident, part vision from folklore.

Soyone (ソヨネ) knew that her journey to Tokyo would likely be a one-way trip. She had made peace with that long ago.

Ten years—that’s how long it had been since her brother, Gōsuke (剛介), went missing. He had vanished along with a specialist team of scientists and military personnel who entered the Tokyo exclusion zone.

Now she stood on the decaying remains of the street where she and her brother had grown up. Her former home loomed ahead, unchanged except for the encroaching greenery slowly reclaiming the concrete metropolis.

Streetlights still glowed after all this time. But their flicker was more than nostalgic—it was a warning. She needed to find shelter soon. These old city streets were no safe haven for someone alone, let alone a well-supplied and armed team. Her childhood home might yet serve as a safe house for her expeditions deeper into the city.
